An indigenous oil firm, Aiteo Oil Exploration and Production Company, has traced the fire incident that occurred within its right of way of the Nembe Creek Trunk Line in Bayelsa State to a sabotage at Awoba field. This was as it confirmed that the fire within its right of way of the Nembe Creek Trunk Line, which was reported on April 21, 2019, has been completely put off. The company had on Sunday declared force majure due to the fire incident on the trunk line, which links Krakama, Awoba, Ekulama and San Bartholomew oil fields with daily output of 60,000 barrels Aiteo, in a statement signed by its spokesperson, Ndiana Matthew and made available to LEADERSHIP in Port Harcourt yesterday, said the confirmation of the sabotage following a visit of to the area by the Joint Task Force on security team. The statement said those responsible for the sabotage and subsequent fire incident had been identified by the security team, adding that the team is set to take necessary action. It reads in part: “Aiteo confirms that the fire reported within its Right Of Way (ROW) of the NCTL on 21 April 2019 has been completely put out. The Security team conducted further inspections at various times yesterday and confirms this position “In line with regulatory requirements, a Joint Investigation Visit (JIV) comprising security and regulatory agencies as well as community representatives and Aiteo personnel will be constituted and deployed to the site to attend to the necessary incident formalities.  This team is expected at the incident site imminently. “The Joint Task Force on Security  team has confirmed that sabotage of the pipeline at Awoba was responsible; has identified some culprits and is set to act as is necessary. “Aiteo is working on further site preparation and mobilisation of specialised equipment to the swamps for further remedial action to facilitate a quick return to full functionality.  Further information will be made available as soon as these occur.”